---


Author Name: **Kelson Gent**
Original Redmine Message: 1804 from https://www.veripool.org



---

DPI context functions are being reordered to follow blocking statements. I have attached an example 
on line 174 of b11.v and attached the generated code as well.

Here is the reordered subsection of the generated C++:
```
// Function: test_func at b11.v:174
++(vlSymsp->__Vcoverage[30]);
if ((0x100U & (IData)(vlTOPp->v__DOT__cont1))) {
     ++(vlSymsp->__Vcoverage[28]);
     vlTOPp->x_out = (0x3fU 
		     & VL_NEGATE_I((IData)(vlTOPp->v__DOT__cont1)));
} else {
     ++(vlSymsp->__Vcoverage[29]);
     vlTOPp->x_out = (0x3fU 
		     & (IData)(vlTOPp->v__DOT__cont1));
}
vlTOPp->v__DOT__stato = 1U;
vlTOPp->__Vdpiimwrap_v__DOT__test_func_TOP(
					   (&(vlSymsp->__Vscope_v)), 
					   "b11.v", 0xaeU);

```

I want to check if this is unintended behavior before reporting it as an issue. I believe this presents a problem because 
the context function has access to the simulation state and should present a non-optimizable barrier during compilation with unknown data dependency.

I have isolated the behavior to two pieces. First, AstNode's AddPrev function has a reorder side effect by using addNext instead of addNextHere.
Trivial replacement solves this issue. Additionally, during the V3Split::splitReorderAll the blocking assign is being moved to precede the DPI CCall.
I don't understand the graph system well enough to come up with a fix without unintended side effects yet, but I can look into it, if this is indeed a bug.

